00:00:00.710 --> 00:00:03.010
In the last video on exponential
functions, we saw

00:00:03.010 --> 00:00:06.380
that functions of the form,
y is equal to some

00:00:06.380 --> 00:00:07.180
number to the x.

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:09.050
Say y is equal to 3x,
which was what we

00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:10.410
used in the last video.

00:00:10.410 --> 00:00:14.630
We saw that these grow very,
very, very quickly.

00:00:14.630 --> 00:00:17.960
So the shape of the graph that
we got in the last video looks

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:21.060
something like this.

00:00:21.060 --> 00:00:22.790
It gets very close to 0,
slowly pulls away from

00:00:22.790 --> 00:00:23.920
0, and then, bam!

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:24.870
It starts to explode.

00:00:24.870 --> 00:00:27.010
This, of course, is when
x is equal to 0.

00:00:27.010 --> 00:00:29.970
So the y-intercept there
is y is equal to 1.

00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:32.990
But the important thing is it
just grows super fast. But

00:00:32.990 --> 00:00:36.090
this was the case where the
base in the exponential

00:00:36.090 --> 00:00:39.430
function is greater then 1.

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:40.280
Here, it's 3.

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:41.900
If it's 2, it'll still
grow quickly.

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:44.840
If it was 10, it would
grow even faster.

00:00:44.840 --> 00:00:46.790
What I want to talk a little bit
about in this video, and

00:00:46.790 --> 00:00:49.990
really just introduce you to the
idea, is the notion of an

00:00:49.990 --> 00:00:52.320
exponential decay function.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:56.530
So this is an exponential
growth function.

00:00:56.530 --> 00:01:00.540
An exponential decay function
has essentially, as its base,

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:02.530
a number less than 1.

00:01:02.530 --> 00:01:04.790
So an example of an exponential
decay function

00:01:04.790 --> 00:01:10.600
would be y is to 1/3
to the x power.

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:17.180
This would be exponential
decay.

00:01:17.180 --> 00:01:20.620
And notice, another way I could
write this, 1/3 is the

00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:23.480
same thing as 3 to
the negative 1.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:26.490
So it's 3 to the negative
1 to the x power.

00:01:26.490 --> 00:01:30.560
I could also write this as 3
to the negative x power.

00:01:30.560 --> 00:01:32.940
This and this are equivalent.

00:01:32.940 --> 00:01:35.440
That's another interesting way
to think about exponential

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:36.380
decay functions.

00:01:36.380 --> 00:01:39.410
It could either be kind of a
standard positive exponent,

00:01:39.410 --> 00:01:42.750
with a base that's less than
1, or you could have a base

00:01:42.750 --> 00:01:46.110
larger than 1, but you're going
to have a negative as

00:01:46.110 --> 00:01:46.980
the exponent.

00:01:46.980 --> 00:01:49.520
So let's plot this, just to
get the general shape.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:51.140
And the shape will always
be consistent.

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:54.260
I'm going to do it for 1/3,
but it's going to have a

00:01:54.260 --> 00:01:58.010
similar shape for 1/2, or
for 1/10, or for 1/100.

00:01:58.010 --> 00:02:00.320
It'll just be scaled
up or down.

00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:02.050
So let's plot a few.

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:06.890
Let's have some x values and
let's have some y values.

00:02:06.890 --> 00:02:10.580
So let's start with
some small values.

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:14.380
So let's say that x is
equal to negative 3.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:19.200
Well, what is 1/3 to the
negative 3 power?

00:02:19.200 --> 00:02:23.740
1/3 to the negative 3, that's
the same thing as 3 to the

00:02:23.740 --> 00:02:27.440
third power, which
is equal to 81.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:28.310
Let's do another point.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:30.070
What about negative 2?

00:02:30.070 --> 00:02:32.800
1/3 to the negative 2 power.

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:37.380
It's the same thing as 1 over--
Sorry, it's equal to 1

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:41.470
over 1/3 squared, which the
same thing as 3 squared.

00:02:41.470 --> 00:02:43.840
You just take the inverse of
the number, get rid of the

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:47.590
negative and that is equal
to equal to 9.

00:02:47.590 --> 00:02:49.620
Oh, I got this one
wrong up here.

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:50.890
3 cubed isn't 81.

00:02:50.890 --> 00:02:52.140
That's 3 to the fourth.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:56.010
3 times 3 times 3 is 27.

00:02:56.010 --> 00:02:58.980
My brain is malfunctioning.

00:02:58.980 --> 00:03:03.040
What about when x is equal to
negative 1, then you have 1/3

00:03:03.040 --> 00:03:06.370
to the negative 1 power.

00:03:06.370 --> 00:03:08.280
which is just 3.

00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:12.030
What about when x
is equal to 0?

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:14.860
When x is equal to 0, remember,
anything to the 0

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:17.070
power is 1.

00:03:17.070 --> 00:03:19.360
And then let's go to a couple
of larger numbers.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:21.630
When x is equal to
1, what is y?

00:03:21.630 --> 00:03:24.990
1/3 to the 1 power is 1/3.

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:26.770
Let's do one more.

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:32.920
When x is equal to 2, we have
1/3 squared, which is 1/9.

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:39.200
So let's plot this exponential
decay function right here.

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:40.590
I want to draw it reasonably
neatly.

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:46.870
And all of these values, once
