This is exponential decay.

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:19.800
And either way, in exponential
functions,

00:05:19.800 --> 00:05:22.470
things happen quickly.

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:26.330
Now, using what we know about
exponential decay functions,

00:05:26.330 --> 00:05:30.460
let's do an actual
word problem.

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:31.320
Let me read it here.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:34.545
It says, a person is infected
by a bacterial infection.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:44.110
And they say, when he goes to
the doctor, the population of

00:05:44.110 --> 00:05:46.200
bacteria is 2 million.

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:55.696
So at the start, he's got 2
million little critters, 2

00:05:55.696 --> 00:05:58.260
million bacteria.

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:01.140
The doctor prescribes an
antibiotic which kills

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:04.700
bacteria, that reduces the
bacteria to 1/4 of its

00:06:04.700 --> 00:06:06.655
population each day.

00:06:11.460 --> 00:06:19.060
So we have the antibiotic and
it cuts down the population.

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:33.430
So it reduces population
to 1/4 of the previous

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:39.270
population each day.

00:06:39.270 --> 00:06:41.020
So they ask us a couple
of things.

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:44.920
Draw the graph of the size of
the bacteria population

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:46.840
against time in days.

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:47.870
So let's draw this.

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.960
So day, and then population.

00:06:56.870 --> 00:07:00.250
So let's say on day 0, before
you went to the doctor, your

00:07:00.250 --> 00:07:04.060
population is going
to be 2 million.

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:06.750
Now on day 1, what happens?

00:07:06.750 --> 00:07:09.450
On day 1 you've taken their
antibiotic, right?

00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:11.540
The antibiotic is starting
right there.

00:07:11.540 --> 00:07:14.510
So it reduces it to 1/4 of
your previous population.

00:07:14.510 --> 00:07:18.090
So now your population is
going to be 1/4 times 2

00:07:18.090 --> 00:07:25.620
million, which is equal
to 500,000.

00:07:25.620 --> 00:07:27.800
Then on day 2, what happens?

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:29.940
On day 2, it's going
to be 1/4 of this.

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:32.660
It's going to be 1/4 of
your previous day.

00:07:32.660 --> 00:07:37.790
1/4 of 1/4 of your previous
2 million.

00:07:40.470 --> 00:07:46.450
So it's 1/4 of this 500,000
which is 125,000.

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:49.450
I think you're starting to see
the pattern that's emerging.

00:07:49.450 --> 00:07:51.010
On day 3, what's
it going to be?

00:07:51.010 --> 00:07:53.140
It's going to be 1/4
times this thing.

00:07:53.140 --> 00:08:00.720
So it's going to be 1/4 times
this 1/4 times 1/4 times 1/4

00:08:00.720 --> 00:08:03.890
times 2 million.

00:08:03.890 --> 00:08:07.000
Which is essentially 125,000
divided by 4, but the

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:10.890
important thing is, I want
you to see this pattern.

00:08:10.890 --> 00:08:14.730
In general, the population
at day n-- Let me write

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:16.400
this in a new color.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:25.850
The population on day n is going
to be equal to what?

00:08:25.850 --> 00:08:29.600
It's going to be equal to 1/4
to the n power, right?

00:08:29.600 --> 00:08:30.730
This is day n.

00:08:30.730 --> 00:08:32.630
On the third day, it was
1/4 to the third

00:08:32.630 --> 00:08:33.700
power times 2 million.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:36.659
On day 2, it was 1/4 to
the second power.

00:08:36.659 --> 00:08:38.799
On day 1 it was 1/4 to
the first power.

00:08:38.799 --> 00:08:41.690
On day 0, there is actually
1/4 to the 0 power, right?

00:08:41.690 --> 00:08:42.799
That's 1.

00:08:42.799 --> 00:08:48.660
So it's 1/4 to the nth power
times our starting population,

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:51.606
times 2 million.

00:08:54.710 --> 00:08:59.310
And if we were to graph it,
using at least just the points

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:01.870
that we have here, we're only
going to be dealing with

00:09:01.870 --> 00:09:03.630
positive x's.

00:09:03.630 --> 00:09:07.360
So on day 0, we start
at 2 million.

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:08.690
So let's say this
is a million.

00:09:08.690 --> 00:09:10.520
So on day 0, we're
at 2 million.

00:09:10.520 --> 00:09:14.780
On day 1, we're at
1/4 of that.

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:19.300
So let's say that's 1 million,
so then that is 500,000.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:23.190
On day 2, we're 1/4 of
this, so this is

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:26.160
250,000, that's 125,000.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:28.770
And then on day 3, we're
1/4 of that.

00:09:28.770 --> 00:09:32.420
So you see the population of our
bacteria really goes down

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:33.150
very quickly.

00:09:33.150 --> 00:09:35.250
It never gets quite to 0.

00:09:35.250 --> 00:09:37.310
We're always going to
have some bacteria.

00:09:37.310 --> 00:09:39.340
Well, eventually you're going
to have 1 bacteria, and you

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:40.310
can get the antibiotic.

00:09:40.310 --> 00:09:42.690
And it's going to have a 1/4
chance of hitting it so,

00:09:42.690 --> 00:09:46.690
maybe, eventually you'll get to
0, but it slowly gets to 0.

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:51.900
But the absolute number
decreases very, very fast.

00:09:51.900 --> 00:09:55.850
Now they also ask us, find
the size of the bacteria

00:09:55.850 --> 00:09:59.660
population 10 days after the
drug was first taken.

00:10:05.250 --> 00:10:06.960
So that's just n
is equal to 10.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:09.870
So it's going to be equal
to 1/4 to the tenth

00:10:09.870 --> 00:10:13.300
power times 2 million.

00:10:13.300 --> 00:10:17.000
Let's take our calculator out
to calculate to this.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:25.490
So let's take 1 divided by
